        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Method"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Make the streusel"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Combine the streusel flour, brown sugar, and cinnamon in a bowl. Add the cold diced butter and rub in with your fingertips until the mixture clumps into pea-to-grape-sized pieces. Do not over-rub to a sandy texture. Refrigerate while you make the batter."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Make the batter"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Heat the oven to 175°C fan. Grease a 23 cm square tin and line with baking paper. Beat the softened butter with the caster sugar until pale and fluffy, 3 minutes. Add the eggs one at a time, then the vanilla. Fold in the soured cream. Sift over the flour, baking powder, bicarbonate of soda, and salt, and fold in with a spatula until just combined."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Layer and bake"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Spread half the batter in the tin. Scatter over half the streusel. Spoon the remaining batter over the top and spread carefully. Scatter the rest of the streusel evenly. Bake for 38 to 42 minutes, until a skewer through the centre comes out clean and the streusel is deep golden. The centre should feel set when pressed; it will be firm but not springy. Cool in the tin for 20 minutes before lifting out. The streusel softens slightly as the cake cools."
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
